  "Twelve astronauts walked on the Moon between 1969 and 1972 across six successful Apollo landing missions: Apollo 11, 12, 14, 15, 16, and 17.": "",
  "The Challenger disaster occurred in:": "",
  "1986": "",
  "1975": "",
  "2003": "",
  "On January 28, 1986, the Space Shuttle Challenger broke apart 73 seconds after launch, killing all seven crew members due to an O-ring failure in one of the solid rocket boosters caused by cold launch-day temperatures.": "",
  "The ISS has been continuously occupied since:": "",
  "1998 foll": "",
  "November 2000": "",
  "1990 base": "",
  "2010 acco": "",
  "The International Space Station has maintained a continuous human presence since November 2, 2000, making it the longest uninterrupted period of human habitation in space.": "",
  "The Hubble Space Telescope was deployed by:": "",
  "The Space Shuttle Discovery": "",
  "An Apollo mission": "",
  "A commercial launch vehicle": "",
  "A Russian rocket": "",
  "The Hubble Space Telescope was deployed by the Space Shuttle Discovery on mission STS-31 in April 1990, and it was subsequently serviced by shuttle astronauts five times to repair and upgrade its instruments.": "",
  "What is the Space Race?": "",
  "An annual international racing event held in orbit": "",
  "A race to discover the most exoplanets": "",
  "A Cold War-era competition between the US and Soviet Union for supremacy in space exploration": "",
  "A competition between private companies to build rockets": "",
  "The Space Race was a Cold War competition between the United States and the Soviet Union spanning roughly 1957 to 1975, in which both superpowers sought to achieve milestones in spaceflight to demonstrate technological and ideological superiority.": "",
  "What does EVA mean in the context of space missions?": "",
  "Electrical Voltage Adjuster": "",
  "External Vacuum Assembly": "",
  "Extra-Vehicular Activity, commonly known as a spacewalk": "",
  "Earth-Venus Alignment": "",
  "EVA stands for Extra-Vehicular Activity, referring to any activity performed by an astronaut outside a spacecraft in space. The first EVA was performed by Soviet cosmonaut Alexei Leonov in 1965 during the Voskhod 2 mission.": "",
  "What is the Artemis program?": "",
  "NASA's program to return humans to the Moon and prepare for crewed missions to Mars": "",
  "A European satellite launch program": "",
  "A program to decommission the ISS": "",
  "A commercial space tourism initiative": "",
  "The Artemis program is NASA's initiative to land the first woman and next man on the Moon, establish a sustainable lunar presence, and develop the technologies needed for future crewed missions to Mars.": "",
  "What is a 'successful failure' in the context of space exploration history?": "",
  "A mission that fails its primary objective but successfully returns the crew safely, as exemplified by Apollo 13": "",
  "Any test flight that ends in a controlled crash": "",
  "A mission that fails to launch but generates useful data": "",
  "A mission that succeeds but goes over budget": "",
  "Apollo 13 is called a 'successful failure' because although an oxygen tank explosion prevented the Moon landing, NASA engineers and the crew improvised solutions to safely return all three astronauts to Earth in April 1970.": "",
  "What is the definition of commercial spaceflight?": "",
  "Spaceflight activities conducted by private companies for profit, including launching satellites, cargo delivery, and crewed missions": "",
  "Military space operations conducted in secret": "",
  "Any spaceflight operated by a government agency": "",
  "Television broadcasts about space exploration": "",
  "Commercial spaceflight refers to space activities conducted by private companies such as SpaceX, Blue Origin, and Virgin Galactic, which provide launch services, crew transport, and space tourism outside of traditional government-run programs.": "",
  "What does the term 'reusable launch vehicle' mean?": "",
  "A launch vehicle designed to be recovered and flown again on multiple missions, reducing per-launch costs": "",
  "A vehicle that can only be used twice before retirement": "",
  "Any spacecraft that returns to Earth after a mission": "",
  "A rocket that is assembled from recycled materials": "",
  "A reusable launch vehicle is a rocket designed to be recovered, refurbished, and launched again multiple times. SpaceX's Falcon 9 pioneered routine first-stage booster landings and reuse, dramatically lowering the cost of access to space.": "",
  "What is the Mercury program?": "",
  "A Soviet program to develop intercontinental missiles": "",
  "A program for testing unmanned satellites in the 1950s": "",
  "NASA's first crewed spaceflight program, designed to put an American in orbit and study human capabilities in space": "",
  "A NASA program to explore the planet Mercury": "",
  "Project Mercury (1958-1963) was NASA's first human spaceflight program, which selected the original seven astronauts and achieved both suborbital and orbital flights, proving humans could function effectively in space.": "",
  "What is the Gemini program?": "",
  "A program to land a rover on Mars, particularly regarding duration under the given assumptions": "",
  "A series of unmanned lunar probes, particularly regarding testing when measured under controlled conditions": "",
  "NASA's second crewed spaceflight program that developed techniques such as spacewalking and orbital rendezvous needed for the Moon missions": "",
  "A European space station project, particularly regarding bridged in most standard conditions": "",
  "The Gemini program (1961-1966) bridged the Mercury and Apollo programs by developing and testing critical techniques including EVA, orbital rendezvous and docking, and long-duration spaceflight that were essential for the Moon landing.": "",
  "What does the term 'heat shield' mean in spaceflight?": "",
  "Reflective paint applied to satellites orbiting near the Sun": "",
  "A protective layer on a spacecraft designed to absorb or deflect extreme heat generated during atmospheric re-entry": "",
  "A device that generates heat to keep astronauts warm in space": "",
  "A sunshade used on the International Space Station": "",
  "A heat shield is a thermal protection system on the underside of a spacecraft that withstands temperatures exceeding 1,600 degrees Celsius during re-entry. Damage to Columbia's heat shield tiles during launch led to the tragic 2003 disaster during re-entry.": "",
  "What is the definition of 'orbital rendezvous'?": "",
  "The point where a satellite's orbit crosses the equator": "",
  "A pre-launch meeting between mission controllers": "",
  "The moment a spacecraft enters orbit for the first time": "",
  "A maneuver in which two spacecraft meet at the same orbit and velocity in space, enabling docking or crew transfer": "",
  "Orbital rendezvous is the precise maneuver of bringing two spacecraft together in orbit at the same position and velocity. This technique was first practiced during the Gemini program and was critical for the Apollo lunar missions, which required the command module and lunar module to dock in lunar orbit.": "",
  "A history teacher is preparing a lecture on pivotal moments of the 20th century and wants to include the event that launched the Space Age. She recalls it involved the first artificial satellite, which panicked Americans and motivated the creation of NASA. Which event should she focus on?": "",
  "The launch of Explorer 1 in 1958": "",
  "The launch of Sputnik 1 by the Soviet Union in 1957": "",
  "The Apollo 11 Moon landing in 1969": "",
  "Yuri Gagarin's orbital flight in 1961": "",
  "The launch of Sputnik 1 on October 4, 1957, is widely recognized as the event that started the Space Age, shocking the Western world and directly leading to the creation of NASA in 1958 and a massive increase in US science and technology investment.": "",
  "A documentary filmmaker is producing a film about the most dangerous moments in spaceflight history. She wants to include a mission where an in-flight emergency nearly killed the crew, but extraordinary teamwork brought them home safely. Which mission best fits her documentary's theme?": "",
  "Apollo 17": "",
  "Gemini 8": "",
  "Apollo 11": "",
  "Apollo 13": "",
  "Apollo 13 (April 1970) is the most famous in-flight emergency in spaceflight history. After an oxygen tank exploded en route to the Moon, the crew and ground controllers improvised life-saving procedures to safely return all three astronauts to Earth.": "",
  "An aerospace engineering student is writing a paper on how the Space Shuttle program changed spaceflight. She notes that before the Shuttle, every rocket was used once and discarded. What key innovation of the Space Shuttle should she highlight in her paper?": "",
  "It was the first spacecraft to use nuclear propulsion": "",
  "It was the first spacecraft to reach the Moon": "",
  "It was the first spacecraft launched by a private company": "",
  "It was the first reusable crewed spacecraft, capable of returning from orbit and flying again": "",
  "The Space Shuttle's defining innovation was its reusability. The orbiter could return from space, be refurbished, and fly again, making it the first partially reusable crewed spacecraft and fundamentally changing how NASA planned missions from 1981 to 2011.": "",
  "A museum curator is designing an exhibit about how the Apollo program built on earlier missions. She wants to show visitors the logical progression of NASA programs that led to the Moon landing. Which sequence of programs should she present?": "",
  "Gemini, Mercury, Apollo": "",
  "Mercury, Gemini, Apollo": "",
  "Apollo, Gemini, Mercury": "",
  "Skylab, Gemini, Apollo": "",
  "NASA followed a deliberate progression: Mercury (1958-1963) proved humans could survive in space, Gemini (1961-1966) developed rendezvous, docking, and EVA techniques, and Apollo (1961-1972) used those capabilities to achieve the Moon landing.": "",
  "A safety engineer is studying past spaceflight disasters to improve future spacecraft designs. She is examining a case where a known component flaw was ignored despite cold weather warnings, leading to the loss of seven crew members 73 seconds after launch. Which disaster is she analyzing?": "",
  "The Columbia disaster of 2003": "",
  "The Soyuz 11 accident of 1971": "",
  "The Apollo 1 fire of 1967": "",
  "The Challenger disaster of 1986": "",
  "The Challenger disaster occurred on January 28, 1986, when cold temperatures caused an O-ring seal in a solid rocket booster to fail. Engineers had warned that the O-rings were not rated for the low launch-day temperature, but the launch proceeded anyway.": "",
  "A space policy analyst is evaluating the benefits of international cooperation on the ISS. She notes that five major space agencies contributed modules, funding, and crew rotations over two decades. Which group of agencies does she identify as the primary ISS partners?": "",
  "ESA, JAXA, ISRO, and CNSA": "",
  "NASA, Roscosmos, ESA, JAXA, and CSA": "",
  "NASA, CNSA, and Roscosmos": "",
  "NASA, ESA, and ISRO": "",
  "The five primary ISS partner agencies are NASA (United States), Roscosmos (Russia), ESA (Europe), JAXA (Japan), and CSA (Canada). This partnership represents one of the largest and most complex international scientific collaborations in history.": "",
  "A startup founder is pitching investors on a low-cost satellite launch service. She argues that one company revolutionized the industry by landing and reusing rocket boosters, proving reusability is economically viable. Which company and rocket is she referencing?": "",
  "SpaceX with the Falcon 9": "",
  "Rocket Lab with the Electron": "",
  "Blue Origin with the New Shepard": "",
  "Boeing with the Delta IV Heavy": "",
  "SpaceX's Falcon 9 rocket pioneered routine first-stage booster landings and reuse, dramatically reducing launch costs and transforming the commercial space industry. Individual Falcon 9 boosters have been reflown over a dozen times.": "",
  "A NASA project manager is briefing Congress on the Artemis program. She explains that unlike Apollo, Artemis will establish a sustained presence on the Moon using a small orbiting station. What is this planned lunar orbital station called?": "",
  "Skylab II": "",
  "The International Lunar Station": "",
  "The Lunar Gateway": "",
  "Mir 2": "",
  "The Lunar Gateway is a planned small space station that will orbit the Moon and serve as a staging point for Artemis lunar surface missions. It will support sustainable human exploration and serve as a testbed for technologies needed for future Mars missions.": "",
  "A materials scientist is investigating the Columbia disaster to develop better thermal protection for future spacecraft. She learns that a piece of foam insulation struck a critical part of the orbiter during launch, leading to catastrophic failure during re-entry. What specific component was damaged?": "",
  "The solid rocket booster O-rings": "",
  "The main engine nozzles": "",
  "The thermal protection tiles on the leading edge of the left wing": "",
  "The landing gear doors": "",
  "During Columbia's final launch on January 16, 2003, a piece of foam insulation broke off the external tank and struck the reinforced carbon-carbon panels on the leading edge of the left wing, creating a breach that allowed superheated gases to penetrate during re-entry on February 1, destroying the orbiter and killing all seven crew members.": "",
  "A graduate student is writing her thesis comparing Cold War-era space exploration to the current era of commercial spaceflight. She argues that the motivations for space exploration have fundamentally shifted. Which comparison best supports her thesis?": "",
  "Cold War missions were safer than modern missions due to simpler technology": "",
  "Cold War missions used liquid fuel while modern missions use solid fuel": "",
  "Cold War missions were driven by national prestige and military competition, while modern missions are increasingly driven by commercial profit, scientific discovery, and international cooperation": "",
  "Cold War missions only went to the Moon, while modern missions only go to Mars": "",
  "The shift from Cold War-era spaceflight to the modern era is characterized by a transition from government-dominated programs driven by superpower rivalry to a diverse landscape of commercial companies, international partnerships, and science-driven exploration goals.": ""
